@node WBTools "Workbench Tool Types"
WORKBENCH TOOL TYPES FOR OPALPAINT

In  Workbench  2.x  and  higher,  Tool  Types  are  used to specify startup
parameters  to  programs  run from the Workbench and are entered and edited
from  the  Icon  Information  screen.   For  instructions  about adding and
editing Tool Types consult your Workbench Reference manual.

The following Tool Types are allowable from the WorkBench:

        PAGEWIDTH=N		Set initial page width
        PAGEHEIGHT=N		Set initial page height
        HORIZRES=HIRES		The startup page must be Hires
        VERTRES=INTERLACED	The startup page must be Interlaced
        SCANWIDTH=OVERSCAN      The startup page must be overscan

See Also
        @{"CLI Parameters" link CLIParms}

@ENDnode


@node CLIParms "CLI Parameters"
CLI PARAMETERS FOR OPALPAINT

You  may  wish  to  start OpalPaint the CLI to add an "OpalPaint" button to
utility  programs  such  as  Directory  Opus  or  write an ARexx script and
include Opal programs to demo and multi-media scripts.

The command line syntax is:

	OpalPaint [Options] [ImageName]

Where: [Options] can be:

	-h		The startup page should be hires.
	-i		The startup page should be interlaced.
	-o		The startup page should be overscan .
	-pw n	        Set the startup page width to n pixels.
	-ph n		Set the startup page height to n pixels.
	-q		Quiet, don't display About requester (for ARexx call).
	-r script	Execute ARexx script on startup.

See Also
        @{"Workbench ToolTypes" link WBTools}

@ENDnode


@node Constraint "Constraint Keys"
CONSTRAINT KEYS

Lines and Freehand

Shift  -  Holding  either  shift key down at any time will lock the brush's
movement  in  either the horizontal or vertical direction, depending on the
direction first moved immediately after pushing the key.  Releasing the key
will remove the constraint and allow free movement of the brush.

Ellipses and Circles

Shift  -  Holding  either  shift key down before beginning the ellipse will
draw,  modify  or  cut  a  circle  by  forcing  the vertical and horizontal
diameters  of  the  ellipse to equal length.  Note that since the pixels on
most  monitors  are  not  square,  the  resulting circle, although the same
number  of  pixels  in  diameter horizontally as vertically, may not appear
perfectly  circular  on  the screen.  This can be fixed using the @{"Be Square" link BeSquare}
option  on  the Preferences screen in the Extras Menu.  This option adjusts
squares  and  circles  so  they are the same apparent height and width on a
monitor.

Rectangles and Squares

Shift  -  Holding either shift key down before beginning the rectangle will
draw or modify a square by forcing the vertical and horizontal diameters of
the  ellipse  to equal length.  Note that since the pixels on most monitors
are not square, the resulting square, although the same number of pixels in
diameter  horizontally  as vertically, may not appear perfectly square on
the  screen.   This  can  be  fixed  by setting the @{"Be Square" link BeSquare} option on the
Preferences  screen  in  the  Extras Menu.  This option adjusts squares and
circles so they are the same apparent height and width on a monitor.

@ENDnode


