@node ARexxScripts "Writing ARexx Scripts"
WRITING AREXX SCRIPTS

For a full list of OpalPaint ARexx commands see @{"ARexx Commands" link OpalPaint:help/OPArexx.guide/ARexxCommands}.

You  can  create  and edit ARexx scripts using any Amiga text-based editor.
Note  that  if  you  use  a  word-processor  you  will have to save it as a
"text-only" or "ASCII" file.

All scripts must start with a comment.

If  ARexx is generating error messages for command arguments, try enclosing
the  arguments  in  quotes,  this  will  happen  if you try to use negative
numbers  as  parameters  (Arexx  interprets  the  '-' sign as a subtraction
operator).  e.g.

	SetDrawMode 9 -20	Doesn't work
	SetDrawMode "9 -20"	Works

The  spellings  colour  and  color  are  interchangeable in OpalPaint ARexx
commands.  For example, ColourSource is equivalent to ColorSource.

Also  note  that where a command accepts a text Message string it will also
accept the '\n' sequence to signify a new line.  This allows multiple lines
of text to be displayed in the requester.

E.g.  to display 3 lines of text, use

	Okay "This is line 1 \nThis is line 2 \nWow!!!! Isn't this fun!!!"

Note  that if you wish to include a single quote in the Message string then
use double quotes at the beginning and end, and visa versa.  ARexx attempts
to match quotes to determine where the string begins and ends.

ARexx Script Filenames
The  suggested  filename  extension  for OpalPaint ARexx macros is '.oprx'.
The  ARexx support menus in OpalPaint will then be able to easily find your
scripts.

For  convenience  it  is  also suggested to place Opal ARexx scripts in the
"OpalPaint:Rexx" directory.  OpalPaint looks first in this location then in
the  standard  REXX:   pathname.   If  you  enter the script name without a
suffix,  say  MyScript,  OpalPaint will look first for for the script named
MyScript then for the name MyScript.oprx

ARexx Port
The Port name for OpalPaint is:

	OpalPaint_Rexx

Note  that  when  using  other OpalVision programs you will need to use the
correct ARexx port name for that program.

ARexx Return Values
OpalPaint  will  return an Error (RC=10) if illegal parameters are given or
if an error occurs.  For example if a script attempts to invert the stencil
plane  when it doesn't exist, or if there is insufficient memory to execute
a function.

Setup in ARexx
Every  spare  page  has  its  own  setup  information stored for it.  It is
important to remember that any modes or gradients etc that you set up for a
page  are  local  to  that page, so if the active page is changed the setup
information will also be changed.

The  setup data includes gradients, transparency settings, drawing mode and
tools,  stencil  enables,  Paint  source,  Grid  setting, Texture settings,
magnification,  brush  cut  modes,  line  styles,  Flood  fill  tolerances,
anti-aliasing  settings, colour stencil settings, magic wand setting, paper
type, alpha settings, rubthrough modes, and fill modes.

ARexx Drawing Commands
Using ARexx you cannot draw any object larger than the visible display size
(even  if the page is larger).  The drawing coordinates passed to ARexx are
absolute  coordinates  within  the  current page.  If a drawing function is
performed  outside the current viewing area, the view will automatically be
panned  to  that  section.   If  the object being drawn is smaller than the
screen  there  will  be  no problems, but if the object is larger OpalPaint
will  center  the  display the best that it can and clip the drawing to the
visible  area.   Note that the current magnification level will also effect
the  size  of  the  object  that  can be drawn.  Also note that low ChipRAM
(especially  evident  when only 1M of Chip RAM is installed) will result in
the  size of the drawing area being reduced as the Menu Bar "rises" up from
the bottom of the screen.

ARexx Symbols
In  the  ARexx  command descriptions several labels will appear frequently.
The meaning and acceptable range for these symbols are:

PotNum	        =  Paint Pot number. Range: 1 to 260
NozzleNum	=  Nozzle number (artist tool). Range: 1 to 10
PageNum 	=  Spare Page number. Range: 1 to Number of Open Pages
BrushNum	=  CutOut brush number. Range: 1 to 3
GradNum	        =  Gradient number. Range: 1 to 8
DModeNum	=  DrawingMode number. Range: 1 to 18 for built in modes and 19 to 22 for spare (loadable) modes.
SpareNum	=  Spare drawing mode number. Range: 1 to 4

NOTE: Any parameters in brackets [] are optional.

Many  commands  also have a BOOLEAN parameter.  A Boolean value is one that
has  only  2  states,  True  or False.  OpalPaint treats 0 as False and any
other value as True.
e.g: A Typical command accepting a boolean value is:

	Trans 0		/* Turn transparency off */
	Trans 1		/* Turn transparency on */

OpalPaint  will  also  accept  the  words  ENABLE  (=1) and DISABLE (=0) in
appropriate places.  Commands will also accept other labels where noted.

@ENDnode



@node AUSSPEAK "Aus-Speak: An Australian to Rest-of-the-world English Dictionary"

                               AUS-SPEAK
                               =========

                     Compiled by : Pratap Patnaikuni

        Version :  2.40                          Date : 29 Sep 1992
        ---------------                         --------------------

AGRO            Anger; angry

APPLE ISLE      Another name for Tasmania

ARKAROO         An aboriginal word for snake

ARVO            Afternoon

AUSSIE          (pronounced Ozzy)  Australian

AVAGOODWEEGEND  Enjoy your weekend.

AVAGO, YA MUG!  Yelled at a cricket match to get the batter going.

BACK OF BEYOND  Refers to any place that is really far away,
                especially places far away in the outback

BACK OF BOURKE  See "Back of beyond," "Beyond the Black Stump" (N.B.
                latter is more usual than "other side of")

BANANA BENDER   Queenslander (A person from the state of Queensland)

BANANALAND      Queensland

BARBIE          Barbeque (Also bar-b-q or bbq)

BARRAMUNDI      Large species of fish found in warm waters

BEAUT           Applied to something which is exceptional in its class

BEWDY           Expression of full agreement and approval

BICKIE          A dollar

BIFFO           A fight  (to get into a bit of a biffo..)

BIKKIE          Biscuit, {called a cookie in US}

BILLABONG       Waterhole; backwater; pond

BILLMAREE       A sickness an aborigine can get from breaking a dreamtime
                law or command

BILLY           Tin container for boiling water to make tea

BITSER          Mongrel dog

BLOKE           Man

BLOODY          All-purpose semi-profanity

BLUDGE          to get or at least demand something (usually money) for
                nothing, as in "dole bludger," one who goes on
                unemployment in preference to working [the latter
                archaic in these days of v.  high unemployment]

BOBOKA          Aborigine word for frog

BOB'S YOUR UNCLE Expression used to mean "everything will be okay"

BOGAN           Undesirable person

BOOMA           Wonderful ; "It was a booma of a day"

BOOMER          Used to describe anything large

BOONGAREE       Aborigine word for tree kangaroo

BO PEEP, TO TAKE A
                A quick look around

BONZER (adj.)   Excellent, terrific, worthy (pron. "bonza"): "He's a
                bonzer bloke" [archaic]

BOTTLER (noun)  Excellent, terrific (thing, person); often used
                as expression of triumph, e.g. at win of preferred
                racehorse: "Bewdy bottler," "You little bottler"

BREKKY          Breakfast

BRISSIE         Brisbane, or someone who comes from Brisbane (Pronounced
                Brizzy)

BROLLY          Umbrella

BRUCE           A man

BRUMBY          Wild horse

BUDGIE          Budgerigar; Native Australian bird; member of the parrot
                family (also called Grass Parakeet) often kept as pet.

BUGGERED        Exhausted, tired

BUGGERED UP     Broken, useless

BULULKIYA       Aborigine term used to describe any place inhabited by unseen
                spirits or supernatural creatures

BUNYIP          Mythical creature inhabiting billabongs

BURKO, TO CHUCK A
                To go crazy

BYO(G)          Bring your own (grog) to a party or restaurant

CHOOK           Chicken

CHOOK RAFFLE    private lottery with fowl as prize, trad. method of
                raising money

CLOBBER         Clothing or equipment

C'MON AUSSIE!   Patriotic catch-cry, usually heard at cricket matches

COBBER          Friend

COCKIE          Farmer

COCKY           Short for Cockatoo 

COME A GUTSER   Making a bad mistake

COOEE           A loud yell, usually meaning 'are you there', 'can
                you hear me?'

COOLABAH        A type of box eucalyptus tree

COPPER          Telltale, snitch, one who informs on others [Western Aus]

CORROBOREE      An aborigine word for a ceremonial dance, now used to
                describe any get together

CRASH HOT       Very good; "He didn't do too crash hot in the game" [Western Australia]

CRIKEY          Expression of astonishment

CRIPES          Expression of astonishment

CROOK           Something broken, sick, or no good

CROW-EATER      South Australian

CUPPA           Short for a cup of tea

DAG             Idiot

DAKS            Trousers; also underdaks (underwear)

DIGGER          Australian soldier [archaic]

DILL            Anyother term for somebody who is a fool or does something
                foolish

DINGHY          Small boat

DINKI DI        Unmistakably Australian; also the whole truth : "yeah! It
                was a dinky di gold nugget!"

DINKUM          Genuine or honest (Also Fair Dinkum)

DOBBER          Telltale, snitch [Eastern States]

DOCKET          Receipt

DONKEY'S YEARS  A very long time: "owryagoin mate, havn seen ya in
                donkey's years"

DON'T YOU WORRY ABOUT THAT
                Don't worry, (I'll get off this charge) [Queensland]

DOONA           Quilt blanket [ Eastern States ]

DRONGO          A born loser

DUFFER          A cattle thief or rustler

DUNNY           Toilet

DUSTBIN         wastepaper basket, garbage can (usually small)

FAIR GO         A reasonable chance

FELT TIP PEN    Marker pen, texta

FEW SANDWICHES SHORT OF A PICNIC
                A little simple 

FLAMING         Another all-purpose semi-profanity

FLAT OUT        To go as fast as possible

FOOTY           Short for Football (Australian Rules Football)

FOSSICK         To go prospecting or exploring for valuables such as opals

FRINGE          Bangs (hair)

GALAH           Kind of bird; also idiot, fool

GARBAGE BIN     Trash can, small or large

G'DAY           Greeting; hello

GO BUSH         Abandon an urban lifestyle; also disappear, hide from
                authorities

GOODONYA        Congratulations; well done.

GRIZZLE         To complain

GROG            Alcoholic beverages

GROUSE          Brilliant; excellent. [Victoria]  also (vb.) to
                complain, whinge [archaic]

GURRIDA         Aborignal word for the dead

HAPPY LITTLE VEGEMITE
                To be content:  "I'm a happy little vegemite"

HEAPS           Lots;  "There were heaps of people there"

HOOROO          Farewell; goodbye

JACKEROO        Outback cowboy

JARMIES         Pyjamas

JILLEROO        Outback cowgirl

JOEY            Baby kangaroo

JUMBUCK         Sheep

KANGAROOS IN ONE'S TOP PADDOCK, TO HAVE
                To show signs of mental weakness

KIWI            New Zealander

LARRAKIN        Mischievous person

LAND OF THE LONG WHITE UNDERWEAR
                New Zealand - Kiwis call it "Land of the Long White Cloud"

MATE            Friend

MATILDA         Parcel made by wrapping one's belongings inside a blanket

MEAT PIE, AS AUSTRALIAN AS
                Unmistakably Australian

MIDDIE          size of beer glass {smaller than a schooner}

MINT            Brilliant; excellent.  Also, MINTER, MINTEST
                [Western Australia]

MINTOX          Even better than mint. [Western Australia]

MOB             A group, {as in mob of sheep}

MOZZIE          Mosquito

{
MULLOCK HEAP    The pile of waste rock (mullock) near the top of an Opal
                mine  -  the  rubbish  you have to go through to get to the
                real gems.
}

NEVER NEVER     The desert of the far outback or just anyplace very remote

NICK            To steal something

NICK OFF        To leave, usually in haste/surreptitiously, also an
                impolite request to leave.

NONG            Goon, dag, fool

NO WORRIES      All purpose phrase, usually a response when someone asks
